      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I'd be happy to explain. When you make a payment on your student loan, a portion of that payment goes towards the principal, and the rest covers the interest. As the principal decreases, the interest you owe each month also decreases because interest is calculated on the remaining principal balance. So, even though you're paying the same amount each month, the amount going towards the principal increases over time, which helps the principal balance to decline faster. It's like a snowball rolling down a hill – the more you roll it, the bigger it gets, but once you start to push it, it becomes easier to stop it from growing. In this case, your payments are pushing against the growing snowball, helping it to shrink more quickly.",
