    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but it still feels like the math is working against me. is there a specific formula used for this? like how do they actually figure out the exact interest amount for a single month?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, the math behind interest calculation on a declining balance is quite straightforward. The interest for a given month is calculated using the formula:\n\nInterest = Principal Balance x Monthly Interest Rate\n\nThe monthly interest rate is determined by dividing the annual interest rate by 12. So, if your loan has an annual interest rate of 5%, the monthly interest rate would be 5% / 12 = 0.4167%. \n\nFor example, if your principal balance at the beginning of the month is $10,000, the interest for that month would be $10,000 x 0.004167 = $41.67. As you make payments, the principal balance decreases, which means the interest for the following months will be calculated on a smaller balance. \n\nIt's a bit like a game of whack-a-mole; each time you hit (make a payment), the mole (principal balance) gets a little smaller, so the next time you hit, it's a bit easier (less interest).",
